# Non-secret config (recipients, healthcheck URLs, thresholds) lives in a
# single source of truth: state/angelus.env. The cron entry below sources it
# so belfry and the daemon read the same values and can't diverge (B16).
# Copy state/angelus.env.example to state/angelus.env and fill it in.
#
# PATH must include wherever your notification command is installed. Set it
# either here in the crontab or inside state/angelus.env. Precedence: a var
# set in the crontab BELOW the sourcing wins; the file fills in the rest.
# PATH=/home/you/.local/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin
#
# These now live in state/angelus.env rather than here:
#   ANGELUS_BELFRY_SUCCESS_URL=https://hc-ping.com/<angelus-belfry-ping-uuid>
#   ANGELUS_BELFRY_DOWN_URL=https://hc-ping.com/<angelus-daemon-down-uuid>
#
# Belfry's notify() sends a push alert via the command in
# ANGELUS_BELFRY_NOTIFY_COMMAND (defaults to bare 'notify-pat' on PATH).
# Push is the deliberate choice: belfry alerting over email would be
# fate-sharing with the transport it's meant to detect as broken
# (2026-05-29 incident). Set ANGELUS_BELFRY_NOTIFY_COMMAND to an absolute
# path because cron PATH is usually stripped.
#
# ANGELUS_BELFRY_WEDGE_THRESHOLD_SEC (optional) and
# ANGELUS_BELFRY_FAILCHECK_PATH (optional) also live in state/angelus.env --
# see state/angelus.env.example for all the knobs and their defaults.
#
# The entry sources state/angelus.env (set -a exports each var) before
# running belfry. belfry.py also loads the same file in code, so the source
# step here is mainly to put PATH in place for `/usr/bin/env python`.
# The leading '[ -f ... ]' keeps a missing file from aborting the tick.
#
# The entry also exports XDG_RUNTIME_DIR so belfry's drift check can reach
# the systemd --user bus from cron (a stock crontab sets neither
# XDG_RUNTIME_DIR nor DBUS_SESSION_BUS_ADDRESS, without which
# `systemctl --user` can't connect and the drift check fails open to a
# silent no-op). belfry.py also injects this in code as a fallback. $(id -u)
# avoids hardcoding the uid.
#
# Optional: ANGELUS_BELFRY_FAILCHECK_PATH overrides where belfry stores its
# last-seen dispatch-id bookmark for the failure-surface check (default
# state/belfry-failcheck-at). Leave unset unless state/ is not writable.
# ANGELUS_BELFRY_FAILCHECK_PATH=/var/lib/angelus/belfry-failcheck-at
#
# Optional: ANGELUS_SYSTEMD_UNIT names the systemd --user unit belfry's
# drift check asserts the live daemon belongs to (default 'angelus'). On
# each tick belfry compares state/angelus.pid to
# `systemctl --user show -p MainPID --value <unit>`; a mismatch, or the
# unit being inactive while a daemon pid is alive, pings DOWN (someone ran
# the daemon by hand, off-unit -- the 2026-05-29 failure mode). If
# systemctl is unavailable the check fails open (no false DOWN).
# ANGELUS_SYSTEMD_UNIT=angelus
#
# Every line belfry writes to state/belfry.log is prefixed with an ISO8601
# UTC timestamp (e.g. 2026-05-29T14:03:00Z), so the log below can be placed
# on an incident timeline.

*/5 * * * * cd /path/to/angelus && { set -a; [ -f state/angelus.env ] && . state/angelus.env; set +a; }; export XDG_RUNTIME_DIR="/run/user/$(id -u)"; /usr/bin/env python belfry/belfry.py >> state/belfry.log 2>&1
